So what if we wrapped the robot periodic in a try catch?

The whole robot code is already wrapped in a try-catch.

try {

robot.startCompetition();

} catch (Throwable throwable) {

Throwable cause = throwable.getCause();

if (cause != null) {

throwable = cause;

}

DriverStation.reportError("Unhandled exception: " + throwable, throwable.getStackTrace());

errorOnExit = true;

} finally {

m_runMutex.lock();

boolean suppressExitWarning = m_suppressExitWarning;

m_runMutex.unlock();

if (!suppressExitWarning) {

// startCompetition never returns unless exception occurs....

DriverStation.reportWarning(

"The robot program quit unexpectedly."

+ " This is usually due to a code error.\n"

+ "  The above stacktrace can help determine where the error occurred.\n"

+ "  See https://wpilib.org/stacktrace for more information.",

After this, the robot program exits. Whether your robot program exits or crashes, the roboRIO will restart it. Your robot should only act like a brick if your code is crashing repeatedly. With that said, I do recall some cases where the old JVM instance didn’t die, so a new instance wasn’t spawned and thus, the code wasn’t restarted. Idk where the investigation into that went.

By the way, we don’t just reinstantiate the robot instance and rerun startCompetition() because there’s no guarantee the user left static variables in a consistent state.
